00:02:13,680 --> 00:02:16,000
 So we're saying we're going to make a phone.

50
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:18,440
 And it's up to us later to decide

51
00:02:18,440 --> 00:02:20,960
 if we're going to make a phone call or receive phone calls.

52
00:02:20,960 --> 00:02:24,160
 And then this next thing is like to connect,

53
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:28,240
 except this is I am willing on port 90

54
00:02:28,240 --> 00:02:29,440
 to receive the phone calls.

55
00:02:29,440 --> 00:02:32,520
 Now, it turns out there's only one program on port 90

56
00:02:32,520 --> 00:02:33,640
 that can receive phone calls.

57
00:02:33,640 --> 00:02:35,240
 So this might blow up.

58
00:02:35,240 --> 00:02:37,160
 You might try to do this.

59
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:38,520
 I mean, port 9,000.

60
00:02:38,520 --> 00:02:40,400
 And if you run this twice and you can do it

61
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:41,880
 in two windows on your computer,

62
00:02:41,880 --> 00:02:45,400
 the second one will blow up and say you can't have port 9,000

63
00:02:45,400 --> 00:02:47,080
 because another piece of software has it.

64
00:02:47,080 --> 00:02:49,960
 But as long as there's only one running, away you go.

65
00:02:49,960 --> 00:02:51,440
 And that's part of this whole try except thing

66
00:02:51,440 --> 00:02:53,520
 because if you run this twice,

67
00:02:53,520 --> 00:02:54,840
 it's going to blow up the second time

68
00:02:54,840 --> 00:02:58,120
 because you cannot receive phone calls on this server

69
00:02:58,120 --> 00:03:00,200
 on port 9,000 with two applications.

70
00:03:00,200 --> 00:03:02,120
 One application gets the phone calls.

71
00:03:02,120 --> 00:03:03,800
 That's what socket listen says.

72
00:03:03,800 --> 00:03:08,600
 The five on there says, dear operating system,

73
00:03:08,600 --> 00:03:11,640
 if I'm busy handling one phone call,

74
00:03:11,640 --> 00:03:14,560
 you can hold on to four more and queue them

75
00:03:14,560 --> 00:03:16,080
 and then I'll come back and get it for you.

76
00:03:16,080 --> 00:03:18,320
 And that you're asking the operating system

77
00:03:18,320 --> 00:03:19,680
 to queue incoming calls.

78
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:21,640
 Don't just say you're busy, shut down.

79
00:03:21,640 --> 00:03:24,040
 If you didn't say this, listen five,

80
00:03:24,040 --> 00:03:27,880
 if you were busy writing the data for phone call one

81
00:03:27,880 --> 00:03:30,120
 and phone call two came in

82
00:03:30,120 --> 00:03:31,920
 and you weren't ready for it right that instant,

83
00:03:31,920 --> 00:03:33,640
 it would just deny the phone call.

84
00:03:33,640 --> 00:03:35,160
 So that's what listen says is,

85
00:03:35,160 --> 00:03:38,600
 dear operating system, hold those temporarily,

86
00:03:38,600 --> 00:03:41,640
 I'll get back to you, which is how it works.

87
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:44,520
 And then what happens is we go into this except.

88
00:03:44,520 --> 00:03:48,480
 Now this except is I'm at the phone,

89
00:03:48,480 --> 00:03:51,520
 I've registered what my number is and what my extension is

90
00:03:51,520 --> 00:03:53,160
 and I'm ready to pick the phone up.

91
00:03:53,160 --> 00:03:54,040
 Let me know.

92
00:03:54,040 --> 00:03:55,960
 So this except is blocking.

93
00:03:55,960 --> 00:03:58,560
 It stops and it just sits there

94
00:03:58,560 --> 00:04:01,440
 and it can sit there forever.

95
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:04,200
 You know, just literally forever.

96
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:06,120
 If nobody calls it, nothing happens.

97
00:04:06,120 --> 00:04:10,560
 The next line never runs until you blow it up

98
00:04:10,560 --> 00:04:12,000
 or the server goes down.

99
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,040
 So that's except is a blocking.

100
00:04:14,040 --> 00:04:16,320
 And the reason we do this except,

101
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:19,400
 well, we have to establish the phone call first, right?

102
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:22,360
 So then this next line runs

103
00:04:22,360 --> 00:04:24,920
 only when a phone call is received.

104
00:04:24,920 --> 00:04:27,040
 So that means that we, on the browser side,

105
00:04:27,040 --> 00:04:31,240
 we already connected, you know, we made the phone call.

106
00:04:31,240 --> 00:04:33,560
 Now we haven't sent any data yet, right?

107
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:36,360
 And so this is just now at this point,

108
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:39,120
 somewhere out there, there's a piece of client software

109
00:04:39,120 --> 00:04:42,520
 that has done a socket dot connect

110
00:04:42,520 --> 00:04:43,880
 and we have done an except

111
00:04:43,880 --> 00:04:45,720
 and our except has succeeded in the server.

112
00:04:45,720 --> 00:04:48,800
 The connect has succeeded and we are ready to talk.

113
00:04:48,800 --> 00:04:50,520
 So the phone call has been made.

114
00:04:50,520 --> 00:04:53,440
 Now the question is, who's gonna say hello?

115
00:04:53,440 --> 00:04:57,320
 And this is where the HTTP protocol solves our problem.

116
00:04:57,320 --> 00:05:00,520
 The server knows that the client must speak first.

117
00:05:00,520 --> 00:05:02,480
 So it just does a receive.

118
00:05:02,480 --> 00:05:04,560
 Now you'll notice the receive and the send

119
00:05:04,560 --> 00:05:06,600
 are the same function calls

120
00:05:06,600 --> 00:05:09,720
 because it's a two-way thing.

121
00:05:09,720 --> 00:05:13,400
 Whatever the browser is sending, the server is receiving

122
00:05:13,400 --> 00:05:15,520
 and whatever the server sends, the browser receives

123
00:05:15,520 --> 00:05:17,480
 and they can do it simultaneously

124
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:19,400
 if they can figure it out.

125
00:05:19,400 --> 00:05:21,880
 But usually you kind of like say, it's your turn to listen

126
00:05:21,880 --> 00:05:23,960
 and my turn to send and then I'll listen.

127
00:05:23,960 --> 00:05:26,800
 And usually they kind of go back and forth.

128
00:05:26,800 --> 00:05:30,440
 In this, there's only one step.

129
00:05:30,440 --> 00:05:33,080
 The server listens, gets the get request,

130
00:05:33,080 --> 00:05:34,800
 sends the data back.

131
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:39,720
 And so then we're going to read some data

132
00:05:39,720 --> 00:05:41,920
 and we're gonna get 5,000 characters.

133
00:05:41,920 --> 00:05:42,840
 We're gonna get the whole thing.

134
00:05:42,840 --> 00:05:45,520
 Remember it's one line, it has a get request in it.

135
00:05:45,520 --> 00:05:47,880
 It has the optional parameters in it.

136
00:05:47,880 --> 00:05:49,440
 And so we're gonna split it.

137
00:05:49,440 --> 00:05:52,200
 Now again, we've received it as UTF-8.

138
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:55,400
 We've got to decode it for UTF-16.

139
00:05:55,400 --> 00:06:00,400
 I mean, not UTF-16, Unicode inside of Python.

140
00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:02,440
 And then we split it based on new lines

141
00:06:02,440 --> 00:06:04,560
 'cause the get request is on one line

142
00:06:04,560 --> 00:06:06,480
 and header, header, header, header, header, header

143
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:07,640
 and then the blank line

144
00:06:07,640 --> 00:06:09,320
 to tell us that we're into the headers.

145
00:06:09,320 --> 00:06:10,960
 And we're only gonna take in this,

146
00:06:10,960 --> 00:06:13,600
 we're just gonna look at that first line.

147
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:15,160
 We're not gonna do anything with it.

148
00:06:15,160 --> 00:06:17,720
 Most servers actually like look at the line

149
00:06:17,720 --> 00:06:19,720
 to figure out what document to send.

150
00:06:19,720 --> 00:06:20,760
 It's a very simple server.

151
00:06:20,760 --> 00:06:23,040
 It sends the same document no matter what the URL is.

152
00:06:23,040 --> 00:06:25,760
 All we do with the URL is we print it out

153
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:27,680
 to prove that we got it.

154
00:06:27,680 --> 00:06:30,240
 And then we construct a response.

155
00:06:30,240 --> 00:06:34,400
 And in this response, again, go back to RFC 2616

156
00:06:34,400 --> 00:06:35,800
 and it will tell you what this response

157
00:06:35,800 --> 00:06:37,440
 is supposed to look like.

158
00:06:37,440 --> 00:06:39,640
 It sends back a 200 okay.

159
00:06:39,640 --> 00:06:41,360
 Remember this is all the stuff we saw.

160
00:06:41,360 --> 00:06:44,400
 Probably I cut and pasted it from a working thing.

161
00:06:44,400 --> 00:06:46,520
 We tell it that we're sending it back

162
00:06:46,520 --> 00:06:50,840
 in content type text HTML, the character set UTF-8.

163
00:06:50,840 --> 00:06:52,640
 Remember I was telling you that.

164
00:06:52,640 --> 00:06:55,360
 A blank line and then some HTML.

165
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:58,440
 HTML body, hello world body.

166
00:06:58,440 --> 00:07:00,880
 And I'm throwing in these /r/n's

167
00:07:00,880 --> 00:07:04,520
 which is the network's version of new lines.

168
00:07:04,520 --> 00:07:08,000
 And then you will notice that I encode it before I send it

169
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:10,880
 because it's Unicode inside of Python

170
00:07:10,880 --> 00:07:12,720
 and it needs to be sent as UTF-8

171
00:07:12,720 --> 00:07:15,680
 because the phone, when you're in a socket,

172
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:17,240
 the thing that's going across the socket

173
00:07:17,240 --> 00:07:19,800
 almost always is supposed to be UTF-8.

174
00:07:19,800 --> 00:07:21,480
 So we encode it.

175
00:07:21,480 --> 00:07:24,520
 And then because the protocol says so,

176
00:07:24,520 --> 00:07:27,000
 as soon as we send the data, we close the connection.

177
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:30,560
 Now remember that the client had to close the connection too.

178
00:07:30,560 --> 00:07:32,120
 So we close it, it's half closed

179
00:07:32,120 --> 00:07:34,080
 and then the client gets all of its data,

180
00:07:34,080 --> 00:07:35,400
 gets the indication that it closed,

181
00:07:35,400 --> 00:07:36,880
 knows it's finished all the data

182
00:07:36,880 --> 00:07:38,440
 and then the client shuts its side down.

183
00:07:38,440 --> 00:07:40,400
 And so there are two hangups.

184
00:07:40,400 --> 00:07:42,160
 It's kind of like a phone call.

185
00:07:42,160 --> 00:07:44,920
 The person hangs up and then click you hang up.

186
00:07:44,920 --> 00:07:47,160
 Now you can't really keep talking

187
00:07:47,160 --> 00:07:49,120
 but you do want to have both sides hang up

188
00:07:49,120 --> 00:07:51,680
 and that shutdown is what's going on.

189
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:54,320
 And then the rest of this is all try-except

190
00:07:54,320 --> 00:07:55,200
 for various things.

191
00:07:55,200 --> 00:07:56,960
 So we clean up our socket.

192
00:07:56,960 --> 00:07:58,960
 So we don't have to restart our server

193
00:07:58,960 --> 00:08:00,320
 when our software blows up

194
00:08:00,320 --> 00:08:02,400
 and so the rest of it's pretty simple.

195
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:05,760
 And then, so this while one,

196
00:08:05,760 --> 00:08:07,480
 the first browser will talk

197
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:09,160
 and then it'll send some data

198
00:08:09,160 --> 00:08:11,680
 and then it'll go back and wait for the next phone call.

199
00:08:11,680 --> 00:08:12,720
 And that's what's going on.

200
00:08:12,720 --> 00:08:13,960
 The next phone call comes in,

201
00:08:13,960 --> 00:08:16,880
 it sees a get request, it sends the data back

202
00:08:16,880 --> 00:08:19,080
 then goes and waits for another phone call.

203
00:08:19,080 --> 00:08:20,760
 So this is an infinite loop

204
00:08:20,760 --> 00:08:22,920
 that sits and waits for incoming phone calls

205
00:08:22,920 --> 00:08:25,360
 and it answers the same thing.

206
00:08:25,360 --> 00:08:27,680
 So it's like you call this phone number

207
00:08:27,680 --> 00:08:31,880
 and it goes, and you go, I would like a pizza.

208
00:08:31,880 --> 00:08:34,480
 And it says, hello world, and then click

209
00:08:34,480 --> 00:08:37,640
 and then you call it up and say, I would like a car.

210
00:08:37,640 --> 00:08:39,960
 And it says, hello world, click.

211
00:08:39,960 --> 00:08:43,480
 And then you say, I would like to register for this class.

212
00:08:43,480 --> 00:08:44,800
 And it says, hello world, click.

213
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:47,200
 So this is not a very flexible server.

214
00:08:47,200 --> 00:08:49,240
 You will build far more flexible servers

215
00:08:49,240 --> 00:08:51,920
 but it's the one I could build

216
00:08:51,920 --> 00:08:56,040
 and fit on a single page in a slide deck.

